caption.text:
Anyone else ever had their Reel show up on the “wrong side” of Instagram?

By the “wrong side,” I mean when your Reel reaches a group of people who you were not trying to reach, and that group really doesn’t understand.

This often leads to a lot of confused comments, or worse: haters and trolls.

Unfortunately, sometimes it’s inevitable, but here are some tips to avoid ending up on the “wrong side” of Instagram:

1. Use specific language — notice how in this reel, I say “reach non followers.” The average person doesn’t know or care what that means, so they’re likely to just keep scrolling.

2. Call the intended audience out by name — if possible, refer to the group you want to reach in the content.

3. Keep it niche — as always, your reels should be related to your niche. Just because something is cute or funny doesn’t mean you should post it!

Have you ever had your Reels reach the wrong side of Instagram?

caption.text:
The stats that matter most:

1. SHARES - More shares equals more views! Shareworthy content is the best way to reach new people and grow!

2. FOLLOWERS FROM POST - If a post generated a lot of followers, then I know that that topic really connects with people and I should make more posts like that!

3. COMMENTS (long ones) - Long comments really show that people are paying attention. Comments like "cool" and "nice post" don't take much thought, but long comments show true engagement!

If you want the checklist I use before every post, comment "check" and I'll send it to ya.

reusable_text_info.text: Should we all stop using the phrase “side hustle” and start calling them “side quests”?

caption.text:
On your marks, get set, GO! (Bonus tips below)

I hear the same thing every day:
"The post I spent the most time on did the worst,
And the post I spent the least time on did the best"

So... LET'S START CREATING AND STOP WORRYING ABOUT ALL THE DETAILS!

Trying to make your posts perfect is overwhelming!
But when you're limited to a 30 minute timer, you don't have time to make it perfect!

Here are some things I find helpful:

1. When I don't have fresh ideas, I remake old videos that did well

2. I film one sentence at a time, that way, I don't have to remember my whole script

3. B-Roll Reels are a creators best friend! You likely already have videos in your camera roll that you can use as content

4. Don't overthink it! No one else is paying as much attention to your Reels are you are

5. Rip off the bandaid and JUST PRESS POST

Don't forget to comment "DONE" when you post it and I'll come watch your Reel!

caption.text:
Which day was your fav? (Keep reading)

This Reel is all “B Roll” clips and it’s so easy to make! If you want 20 free b roll ideas, comment “ROLL” and I’ll send it to ya! 🤩

Here’s a recap of the month:
• Enjoyed some Southern California June Gloom at the beach
• Hung out with family in Ibiza, Spain
• Spent lots of time with the pets (Yuki the parrot, Mila the collie mix, & Schatzi the Doberman)
• Had some great podcasts (including one with no pants)
• Went to a boat show & an exotic pet show
• Moved in with my grandparents-in-law (just for a couple months. It’s a long story, but nothing to be worried about)
